Long story short, I have (had) a 2012 Hyundai Sonata; great car had ZERO issues with it until about 8 months ago. As of right now, it has 105k miles on it and a brand new engine with about 5 miles on it. I have been offered 5k from Carmax for it, and I am driving my parents spare Ford Fusion with ~170k miles on it so I am in no hurry to do anything (unless that car shits out on me too).

What I am looking for suggestions is for a commuter car. I drive from my house (right outside Baltimore) into Baltimore which is a total commute of ~7-8 miles each way (depending on backroads/interstate), and I am only driving myself each day. Mrs. Therm has an SUV that we use for pretty much all family driving and longer trips. I am looking for a small(?, at least one with good gas mileage) commuter car that is comfortable and at least a non-unpleasant way to spend my 30-60 minutes a day. When I bought my Sonata, I knew that was what I wanted and it wasn't an issue. Now, I have no idea, I haven't been looking at all because, quite frankly I expected the Sonata to last at least another 50k miles.

I looked at, test drove, and almost bought a 2018 Nissan Leaf that was ludicrously under priced (had been bought and returned with ~6k miles on it), but I hesitated and it got bought while I waffled. So, does anyone have any suggestions for a decent car that I can drive through the city day in and day out? As I sit, the Venn diagram of 'cars I want' and 'cars I can afford' has zero overlap, so I am hoping others have some suggestions that I haven't thought of (which shouldn't be hard as I have no idea ). Thanks!

I commute in Seattle traffic, and I've not had any problems doing so in my Kia Soul. I have internal combustion Soul, but they also make an EV version of it. I'm not a small person, but the Soul is roomy enough to be comfortable, has enough cargo space* to carry things if I need to, and is easy to park. Gas milage is between 25-30 mpg and I've had no major maintenance headaches with it. I did just have to take it in for a recall, where they reprogramed some sensor settings. Mine is old enough that it doesn't have Android Auto, but newer versions do. Mine does have Bluetooth sync, Sirius radio, USB, and an aux port for you technology needs.

*Admittedly, it's not a pick up truck or a van but seldom do I need that much carrying capacity. And parking either in downtown Seattle is a hassle.

I have a friend in the Bay area and she got her Fiat 500e on lease for $100/mo. Uses it as her overall around town/local area car, plugs it in at home (and has some solar on the roof). I've drive it a time or two, it's not bad. You can fold the back seats down and have decent storage for a dog and groceries or what not. For that little if I had a home where I could plug it in I probably would have done that, and gotten an bigger, used tow/haul vehicle.

If you have a house and can plugin, and don't care if it's tiny with limited storage, something more or less Fiat 500e or similar, if you can get it cheap enough, would probably suit amazing. Just don't plan on driving more than 40-50 miles without considering where you'll plug in to get home, but in the Baltimore area I expect there's a decent number of public chargers.

Click to expand...
So regarding the engine. This was a manufacturing defect as JimZ said, however my car was NOT part of the recall for this. I bought this car new, and up until about 102k miles it had given me zero issues outside regular maintenance, then things just started falling apart. I first took it to Hyundai and they said it had no active recalls and that they couldn't reproduce what I was complaining about in November (complete loss of throttle randomly). Between November and April I took it to (easily) six different mechanics until someone found the problem (bad brake switch pusher, which was under recall on nearby cars, but NOT my car). Then after about 4 weeks of it working okay, the entire engine blew. When I got it towed to my regular shop the mechanic told me that the engine was in a complete lockout state and they couldn't even do a manual override, BUT (even though it was out of warranty), Hyundai may be willing to replace it since they know of manufacturing defects in this time period. When I finally got it to a dealership the tech called me and said when the opened the engine up, the oil pan was full of metal shavings and the engine was indeed completely fucked. Combining this with the previous issue of the brake pedal stopper (which seems minor, but would cause the throttle to completely shut off randomly--made getting onto highways an interesting experience) my wife and I have simply had enough. I have put too much money into this car over the past year and we just want to be done with it.
